{
  "texts": [
    "These receptors belong to a large family of G-protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs), with each receptor exhibiting a specific affinity for particular odorant molecules (Dryer and Berghard 1999).",
    "When an odorant binds to its corresponding receptor, it activates intracellular signaling pathways, leading to the depolarization of sensory neurons and the subsequent generation of action potentials (Schild and Restrepo 1998).",
    "The binding process involves either a lock-and-key or an induced-fit mechanism.",
    "Key molecular features such as shape, charge, and hydrophobicity influence whether a receptor is activated.",
    "Many receptors have overlapping binding capabilities, and most odorants can activate multiple receptors."
  ]
}